<div id="review_2602617621" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2602617621" />
    <a title="Doug Dams" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/5501109-doug-dams"><img alt="Doug Dams" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/m_50x66-82093808bca726cb3249a493fbd3bd0f.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2602617621?book_show_action=true">Feb 16, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Doug Dams" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Doug Dams" href="/user/show/5501109-doug-dams">Doug Dams</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780812972825" href="/book/show/147537.Franklin_and_Winston">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2602617621" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer3154820435066131500">This book is about the personal relationship and how it developed between Winston Churchill and Franklin Roosevelt, during WWII. <br/>I learned a number of things about both leaders reading this book. I learned once that Winston Churchill had made PM he looked to the United States to help him beat Hitler. He believed a relationhip with FDR was essential to getting the US in the war. But he was surprised to see how closely FDR&apos;s thoughts were close to his own concerning Hitler. As both men looked to e</span>
  <span id="freeText3154820435066131500" style="display:none">This book is about the personal relationship and how it developed between Winston Churchill and Franklin Roosevelt, during WWII. <br />I learned a number of things about both leaders reading this book. I learned once that Winston Churchill had made PM he looked to the United States to help him beat Hitler. He believed a relationhip with FDR was essential to getting the US in the war. But he was surprised to see how closely FDR's thoughts were close to his own concerning Hitler. As both men looked to each other for support in the war and in the domestic political problems, their friendship grew. The book provides many insights into how each leader approached problems and in their personal traits. <br />I also learned from this book, the heroic efforts made by Churchill and the British people before the US got into the war. And of course I learned about FDR's efforts to drag the US into the war over the protests of his Republican opposition (who wanted to remain neutral). I also learned how both men use personal relationships to gain political goals. This really was evident in how each of the treated Charles DeGaulle and Joe Stalin. FDR discovered Stalin finally opened up to him after he made fun of Churchill. This hurt Churchill immensely and Roosevelt had to do much to mend the fences with Winston. But with DeGaulle, both men didn't like his arrogance and didn't feel the need to get along with him. DeGaulle was too dependent on the British and American armies to free France. As a history book I found this to be an informative book and it provided many insights into both men. Considering the scale of the conflict and the personalities of generals and others these two men showed a great ability to lead. I'd recommend this book to any history buff and to anyone who wants to know more about Churchill or FDR. </span>
  <a data-text-id="3154820435066131500" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


