<div id="review_4072840471" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/4072840471" />
    <a title="Nora Huber" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/13829333-nora-huber"><img alt="Nora Huber" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/f_50x66-6a03a5c12233c941481992b82eea8d23.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/4072840471?book_show_action=true">Jul 08, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Nora Huber" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Nora Huber" href="/user/show/13829333-nora-huber">Nora Huber</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780812972825" href="/book/show/147537.Franklin_and_Winston">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer4072840471" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer1920681974083025603">A bit of a slow start, but it picked up as more history was explored. The author, managing editor of Newsweek, is very left leaning. But he in no way tried to white wash Roosevelt’s faults and mistakes and crass foibles. Of course Churchill had all this too! (He had many foibles, but perhaps not crass). This was an interesting character study of the two men. I for one don’t think there was an ‘Epic Friendship’ here. They knew they had to work together to save the world - literally- and the compr</span>
  <span id="freeText1920681974083025603" style="display:none">A bit of a slow start, but it picked up as more history was explored. The author, managing editor of Newsweek, is very left leaning. But he in no way tried to white wash Roosevelt’s faults and mistakes and crass foibles. Of course Churchill had all this too! (He had many foibles, but perhaps not crass). This was an interesting character study of the two men. I for one don’t think there was an ‘Epic Friendship’ here. They knew they had to work together to save the world - literally- and the compromises had massive implications. This book is a good follow up to The Daughters of Yalta. Same characters - different stories and perspectives! </span>
  <a data-text-id="1920681974083025603" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


